  "title": "LurMotorn — Chess Move Generation",
  "audience": "The developer building LurMotorn (you)",
  "summary": "How LurMotorn generates legal chess moves with bitboards — and how perft proves it correct. It walks the attack primitives, pseudo-legal generation, the deterministic move ORDER the wire protocol relies on, copy-make legality filtering, MakeMove, FEN setup, and the perft test gate. This phase is verified: the full perft suite passes.\n\nLexicon — **Bitboard**: a 64-bit integer, one bit per square (bit S = square S). **Leaper**: a piece with fixed-jump moves (knight, king). **Slider**: bishop/rook/queen, moving along rays until blocked. **Occupancy**: a bitboard of all pieces on the board. **LSB**: least-significant bit. **Pseudo-legal**: a move that is legal except that it might leave one's own king in check. **Copy-make**: testing legality by copying the board, applying the move, and checking king safety — no separate \"unmake\". **EP (en passant)**: a pawn capturing an enemy pawn that just advanced two squares, landing on the skipped square. **Promotion**: a pawn reaching the last rank becomes Q/R/B/N. **FEN**: Forsyth–Edwards Notation, a one-line text description of a position. **Ply**: one player's single move. **Half-move clock**: plies since the last pawn move or capture (drives the 50-move rule). **Perft** (\"performance test\"): count the exact number of legal-move-sequence leaf nodes to a fixed depth; matching long-published reference counts is strong proof the generator is correct.",
  "generated_at": "2026-06-13T14:08:24.943Z",
  "generated_by": "claude-opus-4-7",
  "base_dir": "..",
  "phases": [
