      "id": "01KV0N144FK1JB3YD7ZGPPBT0W",
      "title": "Generating moves with bitboards",
      "summary": "From a position to an ordered list of pseudo-legal moves: leapers and sliders via bitboards, pawns with all their special cases, plus castling. Then a copy-make pass keeps only the moves that don't leave your own king in check.",
      "steps": [
        {
          "id": "01KV0N144HSESTSF46KFZ7STV4",
          "title": "Squares as bits; pop the lowest",
          "code_path": "Games/Chess/Core/Private/Bitboard.h",
          "line_start": 36,
          "line_end": 40,
          "note": "A bitboard is a uint64_t with one bit per square. Move generation iterates a target set by repeatedly popping the least-significant set bit (PopLsb) — which also fixes a deterministic ascending square order, important for the wire protocol. PopCount/LsbIndex use compiler intrinsics.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KV0N144JK3JBF32658XYAVAG",
          "title": "Slider attacks by ray-scan",
          "code_path": "Games/Chess/Core/Private/Bitboard.h",
          "line_start": 101,
          "line_end": 111,
          "note": "Bishops/rooks/queens scan outward along each direction until they hit a blocker (which is included as a capture target). Knight/king/pawn attacks come from constexpr tables computed at compile time. No magic bitboards yet — correctness first; this is the spot to optimize later.",
