          "id": "01KV0N144K3V2QNN3FEFKFPN73",
          "title": "Is this square attacked?",
          "code_path": "Games/Chess/Core/Private/MoveGen.cpp",
          "line_start": 11,
          "line_end": 32,
          "note": "The workhorse behind check detection, castling safety, and legality. It asks the question backwards: pretend a super-piece sits on S and see which of its attacks land on a real enemy piece of the matching type. The pawn case is the subtle one — note the Opposite() trick in the comment.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KV0N144MAD8K3W8SBVC3TKNM",
          "title": "Generate legal moves — and the wire-defining order",
          "code_path": "Games/Chess/Core/Private/MoveGen.cpp",
          "line_start": 67,
          "line_end": 151,
          "note": "The heart of the engine. It builds pseudo-legal moves in a strict, documented order (From squares 0..63 ascending, targets ascending, promotions Q/R/B/N, castles after the king's normal moves), then filters with copy-make. That order is a wire-protocol contract — both phones must produce it identically.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        },
        {
          "id": "01KV0N144MAD8K3W8SBVC3TKNN",
          "title": "Castling, with all its conditions",
          "code_path": "Games/Chess/Core/Private/MoveGen.cpp",
          "line_start": 41,
          "line_end": 60,
          "note": "Castling is where engines commonly get subtle bugs: it checks the right is still held, the squares between are empty, AND the king is not in check, does not pass through an attacked square, and does not land on one. Appended right after the king's normal moves to keep ordering deterministic.",
          "note_comments": [],
          "code_comments": []
        }
      ],
      "diagrams": [
        {
          "id": "01KV0N144MAD8K3W8SBVC3TKNP",
          "source": "flowchart TD\n  POS[Position: per-piece bitboards] --> GEN[Per-piece pseudo-legal generation]\n  GEN --> LEAP[Leapers: knight / king - table lookup]\n  GEN --> SLIDE[Sliders: bishop/rook/queen - ray scan vs occupancy]\n  GEN --> PAWN[Pawns: push, double, capture, EP, promotion]\n  GEN --> CASTLE[King: append castling if legal]\n  LEAP --> PSEUDO[Ordered pseudo-legal list]\n  SLIDE --> PSEUDO\n  PAWN --> PSEUDO\n  CASTLE --> PSEUDO\n  PSEUDO --> FILTER[Copy-make: drop moves leaving own king in check]\n  FILTER --> LEGAL[Legal moves - order IS the wire protocol]",
          "caption": "The generation pipeline. Each piece type contributes pseudo-legal moves in a fixed square order; the king also appends castling. A single copy-make legality pass then filters out moves that leave the mover's king in check. The final ordering is identical on both phones, which is exactly what lets the codec ship a move as a bare index."
        }
      ]
    },
